In computer science, a linear grammar is a context-free grammar that has at most one nonterminal in the right hand side of each of its productions. A linear language is a language generated by some linear grammar. A simple linear grammar is G with N = {S}, Σ = {a, b}, P with start symbol S and rules It generates the language
{
a
i
b
i
|
i ≥ 0 }
{\displaystyle \{a^{i}b^{i}\;|\;i\geq 0\}}
.
